elationship unfolds in two global cities—Dubai, in non-democratic UAE, which holds what is considered the world's largest Catholic parish, and Bangalore, in democratic India, where the Catholic Church, though afflicted by ethnic and religious violence, runs many of the city's elite educational institutions. Vaidyanathan concludes that global corporations and religious communities create distinctive cultures, with normative models that powerfully orient people to those cultures—the Mercenary in cutthroat workplaces, and the Missionary in churches. As a result, global corporate professionals in rapidly developing cities negotiate starkly opposing moral commitments in the realms of work and religion, which in turn shapes their civic commitment to these cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCapitalismxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 0aCatholicsxReligious lifezIndiazBangalore. 0aCatholicsxReligious lifezUnited Arab EmirateszDubai. 0aConsumption (Economics)xMoral and ethical aspectszIndiazBangalore. 0aConsumption (Economics)xMoral and ethical aspectszUnited Arab EmirateszDubai. 0aProfessional employeesxReligious lifezIndiazBangalore. 0aProfessional employeesxReligious lifezUnited Arab EmirateszDubai. 0aReligion in the workplacezIndiazBangalore. 0aReligion in the workplacezUnited Arab EmirateszDubai. 0aWorkxReligious aspectsxCatholic Church. 4aBusiness (General). 4aReligious Studies. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology of Religion.2bisacsh  areligion, capitalism, globalism, Dubai, Bangalore.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G